<p>I have a socketServer accepting connections from clients. Every time a new connection is made, I start a new thread to deal with that connection.</p>  <p>Now, I would like to notify all the clients about an event that happened in the GUI. I have tried using an interface to callback the socketServer, but the server's fields seem to be null.</p>  <pre><code>public interface MyInterface {    void actionPerf (String s); }  public class FLoorPlan  {     public MyInterface listener;      public FloorPlan(MyInterface l) {        listener = l;     }     public FloorPlan(int init) {     //init the object as part of the GUI      }     public void notifyServer() {         listener.actionPerf("notif");     } } public class ServerNew implements MyInterface {     public ArrayList&lt;MultiServerThreadRead&gt; clients = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();     public String testString;     public FloorPlan reference;      public ServerNew() {       reference = new FloorPlan(this);     }      public ServerNew(String s) {         int portNumber = 8511;         serverSocket = new ServerSocket(portNumber);         start2();     }     public void start2() throws IOException {     boolean listening = true;      testString = "modified";     try {         while (listening) {            clients.add(new MultiServerThreadRead(serverSocket.accept()));            clients.get(clients.size() - 1).start();            }     } catch (IOException e) {         System.err.println("Could not listen on port ");         System.exit(-1);     } }     @Override      public void actPerf(String s) {         System.out.println(testString);// prints null         //notify the clients     } } </code></pre>  <p>This throws a NullPointerException on listener.actionPerf("notif"), since, I guess, I create two different objects with the constructors, so I added the reference to ServerNew here:</p>  <pre><code>public FloorPlan(int init) {     listener = new ServerNew();     //init the object as part of the GUI      }  </code></pre>  <p>I can trigger events in a ServerNew object, but obviously it's not the right one since the testString field is null when I print it. I just need a little hint on what is wrong on my design or whether I have a wrong understanding on callbacks and how they work. Thanks!</p>